<font color="#FF0000">NO &quot;BEYOND VIETNAM&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 11 12:47:12 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I worked in Vietnam five years during the war as a pacifist C.O., helping farmers who lost their homes because of the war.  When the war ended in 1975, I stayed to continue or work with the Mennonites to clean up some of the unxploded munitions, such as M-79 grenades, left in the farmers fields.  I wrote some of these stories in a book called &quot;Reaching the Other Side,&quot;  Crown, 1978.<br><br>
Since then, I have visited Vietnam three times, including &quot;my&quot; province of Quang Ngai where I visited the sad site of My Lai where so many farmers lost their lives on March 16, 1968, the day after my wife and I married in Quang Ngai, just six miles away.<br><br>
I talked with a number of folks there who had lost family members in My Lai.  Of course they spoke with sadness  concerning their losses.  But what amazed me was that I detected no bitterness among the folks there.  Somehow, even in my presence as an American who speaks their language, they exhibited an openness and acceptance that made me believe these folks were  in touch with some profound spiritual strengths.<br><br>
As I kneeled in my prayer of grief by the irrigation ditch where so many farmers lost their lives, I felt a little hand on my arm.  Another on my back.  Another on my shoulder.  Through my tears I looked up to discover young children gathered around me, looking into my face with their bright, curious eyes.  In those eyes I saw hope.  Hope for a new generation who could dream new dreams and create a new peace.<br><br>
For these folks, of course, there is no &quot;beyond Vietnam,&quot; for Vietnam is their beautiful home.  But there is a &quot;beyond war&quot; which I believe most Vietnamese have discovered very profoundly.  <br>

<p><code>-- esm@mcc.org  (Earl Martin) </code><p>


